Of a truth, however, this was confined to the men; the women seem to have found something peculiarly fascinating in the worship of Isis, and to have been, from the first, her warmest de- votees. Eitber because the envy of the priests of Cybele, and other exotic divinities, was excited by this marked predilection, or because the attendance on the rites of Isis was made (as it ' certainly was in aftertimes) a cloak for intrigue3 in the consulship of Piso and Gabinius, a furious persecution was raised against her; and she was ba- nished, with all her ridiculous mum- mery, from the territories of the re- public.
